    <item>
      <title>Asking for a letter of reference</title>
      <link>https://msprev.github.io/homepage-public/resources/asking-for-a-letter-of-reference/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 25 Apr 2017 00:00:00 UTC</pubDate>
      <author>Mark Sprevak</author>
      <guid>https://msprev.github.io/homepage-public/resources/asking-for-a-letter-of-reference/</guid>
      <description>

&lt;p&gt;If you want the best possible letter, it is rational to make the referee&amp;rsquo;s job easier.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1 id=&#34;basic-etiquette&#34;&gt;Basic etiquette&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Email politely to ask if the referee would be willing to write a reference&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;If this is the first time the referee writes, give at least 2 weeks&amp;rsquo; notice to compose a letter&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Clearly state for what, to whom, and when, the reference is due&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Once a letter is written, sending it again, or updating it, is relatively quick&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;If you are applying for many positions, consider using &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.interfolio.com&#34;&gt;Interfolio&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo&#34;&gt;Academic Applications Online&lt;/a&gt;, or similar&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Send all the information about (a) you and (b) the job needed to write the reference&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Send updates for the next letter&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Letters of reference lose their value if they are not confidential&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;h1 id=&#34;what-to-send&#34;&gt;What to send&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Information about the position(s) you are applying for, including the job specification and further particulars&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Your current CV&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A list of items that the referee may wish to include in the reference

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Be organised (e.g. publications, teaching, conference papers, knowledge exchange, etc.)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Have relevant details for each item (where, when, what, etc.)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Explain briefly why an item should impress (e.g. excellent scores, prize-winning, journal&amp;rsquo;s acceptance rate)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Samples of work

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Your most recent recent and significant papers&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;If you are a student, as much of your PhD/MSc thesis as possible and a time-line for completion&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;For each sample of work

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Include a clear abstract&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;For draft papers, say where you intend to submit them&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;h1 id=&#34;nit-picking&#34;&gt;Nit picking&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Send all the information to the referee in one email&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use PDFs in preference to other document formats&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Highlight relevant information in the documents (e.g. deadlines, instructions to referees, selection criteria in a job specification)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</description>
